Note:
Windows ARM64 NT System Call Definitions

Defines NT kernel syscall numbers, platform metadata, and registration logic
for Windows running on ARM64 processors (e.g., Qualcomm Snapdragon, Microsoft
SQ series used in Surface Pro X and similar devices).

Windows ARM64 uses the same NT syscall numbers as Windows x86_64. The NT
system service dispatch table is shared across architectures on the same
Windows build. The difference is the calling convention:

x86_64: RAX=number, R10(=RCX)/RDX/R8/R9+stack, syscall instruction
ARM64:  X8=number, X0-X7=args, svc #0 instruction

CRITICAL: Windows NT syscall numbers are NOT stable across OS versions.
The numbers defined here are for Windows 10 21H2+ and Windows 11 (build 19044+).
See windows_x86_64.runa for the same caveat regarding direct syscall usage.

Syscall convention (Windows ARM64):
- Syscall number in X8
- Arguments in X0, X1, X2, X3, X4, X5 (and X6, X7 for extended args)
- Return value in X0 (NTSTATUS)
- Invoked via: svc #0

Reference: Windows Internals, ntoskrnl.exe system service table
           Same numbers as x86_64 for equivalent Windows builds
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Windows ARM64 NT Syscall Number Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Windows ARM64 uses identical syscall numbers to Windows x86_64.
Note: The NT system service table is the same across architectures on the same build.
Note: Numbers are for Windows 10 21H2+ / Windows 11 (build 19044+).

